01:40.657 --> 01:43.290
Sir Crookes: Tonight I
will demonstrate black body

01:43.291 --> 01:45.057
absorption and the forces.

01:49.322 --> 01:56.790
Forgive me, but there is a
more urgent matter to discuss.

01:57.197 --> 02:02.901
My friends, England, and all of
Europe, is facing catastrophe.

02:03.054 --> 02:07.558
The natural fertilizer we have
long used to grow our crops

02:07.559 --> 02:09.506
is dwindling rapidly.

02:09.507 --> 02:12.637
Without it, our
soil becomes barren.

02:12.638 --> 02:16.251
What we are left with is
too many mouths to feed and

02:18.323 --> 02:19.888
not enough food.

02:19.889 --> 02:23.753
Tonight, I call on the
great minds of Europe.

02:23.754 --> 02:27.651
Barring a monumental
scientific breakthrough,

02:27.652 --> 02:33.564
in a few short years,
Europe will starve.

02:35.765 --> 02:37.712
Haber: Did you read what
this Crookes fellow claims?

02:37.713 --> 02:39.853
Millions of people will
starve if we don't find

02:39.854 --> 02:42.093
a new way to grow crops.

02:42.505 --> 02:44.005
I must do something.

02:44.006 --> 02:46.113
Clara: Fritz, you hardly
keep a houseplant alive.

02:46.114 --> 02:47.678
Haber: Guano, do
you know what it is?

02:47.679 --> 02:49.052
Clara: Of course.

02:49.053 --> 02:50.713
Bat excrement.

02:50.714 --> 02:52.950
Haber: And why do we ship
bat excrement to Europe

02:52.951 --> 02:54.387
from a world away?

02:54.388 --> 02:55.793
Clara: It's a good
source of nitrogen.

02:55.794 --> 02:57.166
Haber: So is the air.

02:57.167 --> 02:58.731
80% nitrogen to be exact.

02:58.732 --> 03:01.255
Clara: You could never
harness enough energy to

03:01.256 --> 03:03.811
break apart nitrogen bonds.

03:03.812 --> 03:06.237
Haber: A lightning
bolt could do it.

03:06.238 --> 03:08.921
Clara: Yes, but you can
hardly corral lightning bolts,

03:08.922 --> 03:11.226
now can you?

03:13.873 --> 03:15.762
Haber: Not yet.

03:20.773 --> 03:25.500
Rathenau: Gentlemen, the very
fate of our nation depends

03:25.501 --> 03:27.353
on the men in this room.

03:27.354 --> 03:31.282
Our generals have informed
me that the army's ammunition

03:31.283 --> 03:35.215
stockpile has dwindled
to a six-month supply.

03:35.978 --> 03:40.322
And I say it's nonsense, in six
weeks our boys will be hurling

03:40.323 --> 03:43.101
rocks instead of
firing artillery.

03:43.102 --> 03:45.018
Haber: My God.

03:45.019 --> 03:46.486
Rathenau: I have taken it
upon myself to fund a

03:46.487 --> 03:51.282
military department devoted
to scientific innovation.

03:52.014 --> 03:56.073
Make no mistake, we are
facing a bloody surrender.

03:59.712 --> 04:01.436
I need you.

04:01.437 --> 04:04.566
Germany needs you.

04:04.567 --> 04:07.824
Lenard: You have my
support, Dr Rathenau.

04:07.825 --> 04:09.071
And I'm surely
not alone in that.

04:09.072 --> 04:12.493
Crowd: Hear, hear.

04:13.512 --> 04:15.619
Rathenau: Gentlemen, I
am circulating a letter to the

04:15.620 --> 04:19.005
kaiser, pledging the commitment
of the finest minds of Germany's

04:19.005 --> 04:24.312
scientific community and
I beseech you to sign it.

04:25.171 --> 04:29.678
Stand with the fatherland
in its hour of need.

04:34.147 --> 04:39.708
♪

04:48.011 --> 04:52.641
Albert: Doctor Rathenau, some
of us still indulge in the wild

04:52.642 --> 04:57.944
notion that scientists are meant
to unravel the mysteries of

04:57.945 --> 05:02.644
the world, not find new
ways to destroy it.

05:03.727 --> 05:06.377
Lenard: We are all
free to make choices.

05:06.378 --> 05:08.297
And history will take note.

05:12.958 --> 05:14.075
Elsa: You didn't sign it.

05:14.076 --> 05:15.512
Albert: Of course
I didn't sign it.

05:15.513 --> 05:17.685
I'm not a lemming
like the rest of them.

05:17.686 --> 05:18.867
Elsa: Aren't you
worried it might affect

05:18.868 --> 05:20.559
your standing in the academy?

05:20.560 --> 05:23.403
Albert: I won't
make weapons, Elsa.

05:23.404 --> 05:25.643
I have actual work to do.

05:27.333 --> 05:30.111
Elsa: You must
miss them terribly,

05:30.112 --> 05:33.437
I'm sure they miss you.

05:37.203 --> 05:39.918
Albert: She was welcome to
every stick of furniture.

05:39.919 --> 05:44.773
But how could I let
her take my boys?

05:44.774 --> 05:47.141
Elsa: What choice did you have?

05:53.558 --> 05:55.474
Albert: It's cruel, isn't it?

05:55.475 --> 06:00.841
That what is most important
in life reveals itself

06:00.842 --> 06:03.651
to be so only by its absence.

06:03.652 --> 06:06.909
Elsa: You can't stay here,
alone, in this empty apartment.

06:06.910 --> 06:08.092
Albert: Are you
offering to take me in?

06:08.093 --> 06:09.784
Elsa: Of course not,
you're not divorced.

06:09.785 --> 06:11.445
Albert: Don't start
this again, Elsa.

06:11.446 --> 06:14.288
Elsa: But there is a flat
available in my building.

06:14.289 --> 06:15.758
I could look after you.

06:15.759 --> 06:19.144
Albert: I am quite capable of
tending to myself, thank you.

06:19.145 --> 06:20.198
Elsa: Yes, clearly.

06:20.199 --> 06:22.913
No sleep, a bare
apartment, a flaring ulcer,

06:22.914 --> 06:24.543
you're the picture
of independence.

06:24.544 --> 06:30.068
Albert: I know this empty space
must seem uninhabitable to you,

06:30.069 --> 06:34.030
but to me, such a
vacuum is second nature.

06:34.031 --> 06:36.941
Elsa: Even I know that
vacuums can't sustain life.

06:39.525 --> 06:44.156
Albert: General relativity is
everything to me now, Elsa.

06:44.157 --> 06:47.354
Once I've solved it, the
rest of my life can rush in.

06:47.894 --> 06:50.480
Elsa: You are unbearable.

06:50.481 --> 06:52.816
It's a pity I love you so much.

07:00.831 --> 07:01.948
Besso: Mileva!

07:01.949 --> 07:02.938
How good to see you.

07:02.939 --> 07:04.120
Come in.

07:04.121 --> 07:06.165
Mileva: I'm afraid I
don't have time today.

07:06.166 --> 07:07.186
Besso: Anna was just
setting up breakfast.

07:07.187 --> 07:11.595
Anna, Anna, Mileva
is here, come.

07:11.596 --> 07:13.065
Anna: What a lovely surprise.

07:13.066 --> 07:16.578
Mileva: Yes, well, I only came
by to borrow some sheet music.

07:16.579 --> 07:18.942
I find myself with some
spare time on my hands.

07:18.943 --> 07:21.821
I thought perhaps I
could teach piano again.

07:23.638 --> 07:28.242
Besso: Is everything
all right, Mileva?

07:30.762 --> 07:32.231
Mileva: The money
Albert sent for the month

07:32.232 --> 07:35.137
lasted only a week.

07:35.138 --> 07:36.447
Besso: You must write
to him for more.

07:36.448 --> 07:38.906
He wouldn't want you
and the boys to suffer.

07:38.907 --> 07:40.600
Mileva: He sends all he can.

07:40.601 --> 07:44.629
But with the war, the German
mark is practically worthless.

07:46.286 --> 07:48.813
Besso: I'll go find
that sheet music.

07:52.356 --> 07:54.623
Anna: Has Albert made any
plans to visit the boys?

07:54.624 --> 07:57.785
Mileva: I'm certain
he will soon.

07:57.786 --> 08:00.504
Anna: You are too
kind to him, Mileva.

08:01.459 --> 08:04.944
Besso: I know you will
find students quickly.

08:05.133 --> 08:08.202
Mileva: Thank you.

08:19.731 --> 08:25.963
♪

08:41.611 --> 08:42.760
Ilse: Mama!

08:42.761 --> 08:43.783
Nicolai: Frau Einstein.

08:43.784 --> 08:44.837
Elsa: Herr Nicolai.

08:44.838 --> 08:46.434
I was not expecting company.

08:46.435 --> 08:48.255
And apparently neither were you.

08:48.256 --> 08:51.163
Ilse: Nicolai is only
here bearing news.

08:51.164 --> 08:53.558
Nicolai: Yes, you see I'm
the leader of a new caucus

08:53.559 --> 08:55.634
advocating against the war.

08:55.635 --> 08:58.478
Actually, I was
wondering if you would

08:58.479 --> 09:01.224
introduce me to
Professor Einstein?

09:01.225 --> 09:04.136
Ilse tells me you
are quite close.

09:06.305 --> 09:08.731
I'm told he was the only
scientist who refused

09:08.732 --> 09:10.233
to sign the war manifesto.

09:10.234 --> 09:12.373
The support of a
man of his stature

09:12.374 --> 09:13.970
would help my cause greatly.

09:13.971 --> 09:15.790
Elsa: I'll convey the message.

09:15.791 --> 09:18.734
But Dr Einstein is
a very busy man.

09:20.296 --> 09:25.378
Nicolai: Frau Einstein,
Fraulein Ilse.

09:33.840 --> 09:35.340
Ilse: You didn't have to
treat him with such venom.

09:35.341 --> 09:38.407
Elsa: He's a cad, groping
a young woman half his age.

09:38.408 --> 09:39.620
It's unseemly.

09:39.621 --> 09:41.410
Ilse: You, of all people,
are lecturing me

09:41.411 --> 09:42.687
about what is unseemly?

09:42.688 --> 09:45.243
Elsa: Don't you dare
speak to me in that tone.

09:45.244 --> 09:47.318
And it is careless of you
to insinuate to a stranger

09:47.319 --> 09:49.172
that Albert and I are so close.

09:49.173 --> 09:50.800
Ilse: No one need
insinuate anything, mama.

09:50.801 --> 09:51.695
The neighbors have
been gossiping about

09:51.696 --> 09:53.484
you two for months.

09:53.485 --> 09:56.359
Elsa: You shouldn't waste your
time worrying over my affairs.

09:56.360 --> 09:58.755
Ilse: What I worry over is my
own mother's behavior impeding

09:58.756 --> 10:00.703
my chances of ever
getting married.

10:00.704 --> 10:03.354
You've acted so outrageously
that no self-respecting man

10:03.355 --> 10:05.079
will give me a second look.

10:05.080 --> 10:08.848
Elsa: I will make certain that
you and your sister are settled.

10:08.849 --> 10:11.600
But then where will I be?

10:12.331 --> 10:15.078
When you are older, you will
realize that there is little

10:15.079 --> 10:18.112
for a woman in this world.

10:18.113 --> 10:21.215
One way or another, I must
salvage a life for myself.

10:32.742 --> 10:35.648
Besso: Eduard, is
everything all right?

10:35.649 --> 10:38.463
Hans: Uncle Michele!

10:38.811 --> 10:41.790
Besso: Dear God, Mileva?

10:41.791 --> 10:43.233
Mileva can you hear me?

10:43.234 --> 10:44.643
Hans: She'll wake up.

10:44.644 --> 10:46.470
She always does.

10:46.471 --> 10:47.911
Besso: This has happened before?

10:47.912 --> 10:51.950
Hans: She says her heart beats
fast and then she doesn't

10:51.951 --> 10:54.614
remember what happens next.

10:55.188 --> 10:56.212
Besso: Help me.

10:56.213 --> 10:57.942
Help me lift her.

10:57.943 --> 11:01.183
Hans: She'll all
right, won't she?

11:05.924 --> 11:07.525
Albert: Professor Hilbert?

11:07.526 --> 11:09.961
Hilbert: Ah, Professor Einstein.

11:09.962 --> 11:11.594
Come, come.

11:11.595 --> 11:14.672
I was most taken by your
lecture on relativity.

11:14.673 --> 11:16.145
Couldn't wait to
meet the man with

11:16.146 --> 11:19.514
such a boundless imagination.

11:20.408 --> 11:23.131
Albert: These are
calculations for relativity.

11:23.132 --> 11:24.926
Hilbert: Well I should
hope you would recognize

11:24.927 --> 11:26.945
your own quagmire.

11:26.946 --> 11:28.804
You know, the prickly
points in your theory

11:28.805 --> 11:30.695
have even me at a loss.

11:30.696 --> 11:32.810
For the moment.

11:32.811 --> 11:34.445
Albert: I had hoped to show
you my most recent work.

11:34.446 --> 11:38.547
I never imagined a mathematician
of your stature would actually

11:38.548 --> 11:41.463
put your mind to it
before I even arrived.

11:41.464 --> 11:43.898
Hilbert: I've spent the last
two days puzzling over it.

11:43.899 --> 11:46.238
Albert: I've lost the last
few years of my life trying

11:46.239 --> 11:48.000
to complete the damn thing.

11:48.001 --> 11:51.365
I'm overjoyed that you're
willing to assist me.

11:51.366 --> 11:52.583
Hilbert: Assist you?

11:52.584 --> 11:55.019
Well, that would be fun, but
that would take far too long.

11:55.020 --> 11:59.056
No, no, I can solve it much
more quickly on my own.

11:59.057 --> 12:00.691
Albert: On your own?

12:00.692 --> 12:02.710
Hilbert: Professor Einstein,
physics is far too complicated

12:02.711 --> 12:05.662
to be left to physicists.

12:07.358 --> 12:08.543
Planck: Albert, what
are you so upset about?

12:08.544 --> 12:10.209
Albert: He's going
to finish it first!

12:10.210 --> 12:13.675
Planck: Well consider
yourself lucky.

12:14.440 --> 12:16.587
It's not every day one of the
greatest mathematicians in

12:16.588 --> 12:19.823
the world decides to take up
the cause of a physicist.

12:19.824 --> 12:22.387
Sit down, Albert, please.

12:22.388 --> 12:25.496
Albert: Relativity is the
greatest idea I have ever had.

12:25.497 --> 12:27.899
Is it so wrong that
I want to bring it

12:27.900 --> 12:30.467
to completion on my own?

12:31.457 --> 12:33.348
Planck: Albert, are you really
going to start a public pissing

12:33.349 --> 12:38.474
contest over academic credit
when our boys, my sons,

12:38.475 --> 12:42.357
are out the there
fighting an actual war?

12:42.867 --> 12:46.006
Besides, Hilbert is a
top-rate mathematician.

12:46.007 --> 12:48.249
You'd be foolish to
try to match his pace.

12:48.250 --> 12:51.903
Albert: Max, this is all I have.

12:51.904 --> 12:55.625
Planck: Life is more
than work, Albert.

12:57.801 --> 13:02.161
Albert: I am about to
embark on a great folly.

13:03.056 --> 13:05.014
This will be the first
of four lectures.

13:08.536 --> 13:12.000
I will certainly be dubbed mad,

13:13.889 --> 13:17.637
but by the last lecture,
I will either have tamed

13:17.638 --> 13:23.473
this beast or will
have been trampled by it.

13:29.367 --> 13:33.761
[Inaudible mumbling].

13:41.320 --> 13:43.915
The Lagrangian must be
constructed in such

13:43.916 --> 13:47.861
a way as to respect the
transformations we saw.

13:48.819 --> 13:51.190
Hilbert: Now we can attempt
to construct various

13:51.191 --> 13:53.626
field equations,
analogous to what Maxwell

13:53.627 --> 13:55.969
wrote on electromagnetism.

13:56.959 --> 14:00.195
Albert: This equation works
for planetary orbits

14:00.196 --> 14:02.760
that never shift.

14:02.761 --> 14:06.637
But here the constant shift
in mercury's orbit due to

14:06.638 --> 14:10.518
the constant gravitational
pull of the sun should.

14:13.753 --> 14:18.851
♪

14:24.744 --> 14:29.362
♪

14:35.513 --> 14:41.060
♪

14:48.139 --> 14:53.719
♪

15:00.798 --> 15:03.137
Scientist: Have you solved it,
Professor Einstein?

15:03.138 --> 15:05.796
Albert: Not quite yet, but
the beast is cowering,

15:05.797 --> 15:08.107
that's for sure!

15:09.002 --> 15:11.308
Clara: If only they'd let
women into the academy.

15:11.309 --> 15:13.552
What I wouldn't give
to see Albert sweat out

15:13.553 --> 15:16.019
his calculations in
front of an audience.

15:16.020 --> 15:18.872
It says here he doesn't
sleep, stays up all hours

15:18.873 --> 15:20.699
of the night, working.

15:20.700 --> 15:23.230
Haber: He should be applying
his mind to more urgent matters.

15:23.231 --> 15:25.121
Clara: You certainly are
puffing yourself up just for

15:25.122 --> 15:27.625
making gunpowder, aren't you?

15:28.070 --> 15:30.958
Haber: I am doing much
more than making gunpowder.

15:36.146 --> 15:38.933
By forcing air over the
iron and potassium hydroxide

15:38.934 --> 15:42.555
promoter at such intense
pressure, the hydrogen from

15:42.556 --> 15:46.881
natural gasses combines with
nitrogen from the air, producing

15:46.882 --> 15:52.618
pure liquid ammonia, containing
the form of nitrogen most

15:52.619 --> 15:55.986
easily consumed by plant life.

15:58.002 --> 16:00.885
Bosch: That is not enough
to feed one common ficus.

16:00.886 --> 16:03.963
Haber: We'll build a
large-scale, high-pressure

16:03.964 --> 16:05.469
reactor that would.

16:05.470 --> 16:06.943
Bosch: Blow up a small town?

16:06.944 --> 16:08.577
The pressure you would need
to produce ammonia in large

16:08.578 --> 16:11.045
quantities would explode
any reactor on earth.

16:11.046 --> 16:13.579
Executive: Were you going to inform
us of this risk, Herr Haber?

16:13.580 --> 16:17.550
Haber: We can build
a new reactor.

16:17.551 --> 16:20.050
Bigger, stronger.

16:20.051 --> 16:23.031
Of course, it will take
money, quite a lot of it.

16:23.032 --> 16:26.203
Gentlemen, Germany will go
hungry without fertilizer.

16:26.204 --> 16:30.017
And, I do understand the
difficulty of industrializing

16:30.018 --> 16:31.490
such a process.

16:31.491 --> 16:34.279
But what's in this beaker is
already most of the way toward

16:34.280 --> 16:35.689
a feat no one thought possible.

16:35.690 --> 16:39.342
I have devised a way to pull
nitrogen out of thin air.

16:39.343 --> 16:43.252
I imagine there would be profit
to be had in feeding the world.

16:43.253 --> 16:45.115
No?

16:50.336 --> 16:52.257
Elsa: Albert.

16:52.258 --> 16:54.564
Dear God, have you been eating?

16:54.565 --> 16:57.096
Albert: With the war rations,
nobody's been eating.

16:57.097 --> 16:58.251
Elsa: You need rest.

16:58.252 --> 16:59.565
Your ulcer.

16:59.566 --> 17:01.872
Albert: Relativity is
at my fingertips, Elsa.

17:01.873 --> 17:03.730
I can almost touch it.

17:03.731 --> 17:06.839
Elsa: The universe isn't
going anywhere, Albert.

17:06.839 --> 17:08.345
A little sleep will do you good.

17:08.346 --> 17:11.102
Albert: I had a glorious
breakthrough today, Elsa.

17:11.103 --> 17:13.857
Elsa: Michele wrote
to you five times.

17:13.858 --> 17:16.034
You'd know if you didn't
disappear under a rock when

17:16.035 --> 17:17.928
you throw yourself into work.

17:17.929 --> 17:20.363
When you didn't answer,
he finally wrote to me.

17:20.364 --> 17:21.676
Albert: Has something happened?

17:21.678 --> 17:23.760
- The boys.
- Elsa: They're fine.

17:23.761 --> 17:25.092
It's Mileva.

17:25.093 --> 17:26.582
She's been suffering
from heart troubles and

17:26.583 --> 17:27.856
is recovering in the hospital.

17:27.857 --> 17:30.868
Albert: Who's taking care
of Eduard and Hans Albert?

17:30.869 --> 17:32.214
Elsa: Michele is
looking after them.

17:32.215 --> 17:33.579
Albert: Then they
are in good hands.

17:33.580 --> 17:34.875
Don't worry yourself
over Mileva.

17:34.876 --> 17:36.284
She'll be fine.

17:36.285 --> 17:37.534
She does this.

17:37.535 --> 17:39.073
The woman craves attention.

17:39.074 --> 17:40.675
Elsa: But your boys need you.

17:40.676 --> 17:42.790
Albert: I'll write
to Michele at once.

17:42.791 --> 17:45.198
I'll be there for them as
soon as I finish my lectures.

17:54.136 --> 17:55.833
Nicolai: Dr Einstein?

17:55.834 --> 17:57.211
George Nicolai.

17:57.212 --> 17:59.262
I am acquainted with Elsa.

17:59.263 --> 18:00.865
Surely she has mentioned me?

18:00.866 --> 18:02.306
The committee?

18:02.307 --> 18:03.653
Albert: I'm afraid
I have no idea what

18:03.654 --> 18:05.895
you're talking about, sir.

18:05.896 --> 18:07.865
Nicolai: You see, I'm the
leader of a new caucus

18:07.866 --> 18:09.453
advocating against the war.

18:09.454 --> 18:11.376
Albert: I wish you
good luck with it.

18:11.377 --> 18:13.042
Nicolai: All it would
take is a signature.

18:13.043 --> 18:15.094
To show that men of science
like yourself stand against

18:15.095 --> 18:16.568
the treachery of war.

18:16.569 --> 18:18.041
Albert: It's not that
I don't sympathize

18:18.042 --> 18:19.196
with your mission, sir.

18:19.197 --> 18:22.080
But I'm a scientist,
not a politician.

18:22.081 --> 18:25.765
I've made a name for myself
by refusing to sign my name.

18:25.766 --> 18:28.268
Good day.

18:36.855 --> 18:40.410
Planck: Albert?

18:40.411 --> 18:42.686
This just came for you.

18:42.687 --> 18:46.631
From Hilbert.

18:51.468 --> 18:56.150
♪

19:02.012 --> 19:07.559
♪

19:09.639 --> 19:12.266
Albert: He's done it.

19:12.267 --> 19:16.948
He's completed
the last equation.

19:19.189 --> 19:20.758
He's defeated me.

19:20.759 --> 19:22.360
Planck: I'm so sorry, Albert.

19:22.361 --> 19:25.213
Albert: I was so close, max.

19:25.214 --> 19:27.328
Planck: The theory
is still yours.

19:27.329 --> 19:31.109
No one can take
that away from you.

19:31.110 --> 19:32.904
The final calculation?

19:32.905 --> 19:35.052
Merely a footnote.

19:35.053 --> 19:40.215
And, at least now you can
go see your boys, yes?

19:48.961 --> 19:50.979
Mileva: Thank you for
looking after them, Michele.

19:50.980 --> 19:53.478
But you won't have to be
burdened by these two rascals

19:53.479 --> 19:58.514
much longer, the doctor says
I can go home in two days!

19:59.056 --> 20:01.298
Hans: Just in time!

20:01.299 --> 20:02.836
Mileva: Just in time for what?

20:02.837 --> 20:04.727
Besso: I received a letter.

20:04.728 --> 20:05.945
From Albert.

20:05.946 --> 20:07.643
He is coming to Zurich.

20:07.644 --> 20:12.070
Hans: Isn't it wonderful, mama?

20:16.265 --> 20:22.133
[Heavy breathing].

20:28.668 --> 20:33.954
♪

20:33.955 --> 20:35.749
Swiss soldier: By order of
the federal council,

20:35.750 --> 20:38.825
all Swiss borders have
been closed due to the war!

20:38.826 --> 20:41.390
This train and all passengers
will be turned back to Germany.

20:41.391 --> 20:42.607
Albert: Excuse me.

20:42.608 --> 20:46.004
I have a Swiss passport,
here let me show you.

20:46.005 --> 20:47.254
Swiss soldier: The train
is going back, sir.

20:47.255 --> 20:48.696
Albert: But I must see my sons.

20:48.697 --> 20:50.010
Their mother is ill, surely.

20:50.011 --> 20:52.093
Swiss soldier: No
exceptions, sir.

20:52.094 --> 20:54.176
By order of the federal council,

20:54.177 --> 20:57.353
all Swiss borders have
been closed due to the war!

21:05.137 --> 21:08.698
Besso: It's getting cold.

21:11.028 --> 21:12.374
Come inside, Hans.

21:12.375 --> 21:13.784
Have some cocoa.

21:13.785 --> 21:16.219
Hans: Just a little
longer, uncle Michele.

21:16.220 --> 21:18.078
He's coming.

21:18.079 --> 21:21.767
I know it.

21:24.039 --> 21:29.907
♪

21:37.149 --> 21:40.100
Butler: Good evening, sir.

21:40.995 --> 21:42.628
General: Frau Haber, I presume.

21:42.629 --> 21:45.260
I have an appointment
with your husband.

21:45.719 --> 21:47.032
Clara: At this hour?

21:47.033 --> 21:49.257
General: Would you inform
him that General Lehning

21:49.258 --> 21:50.412
is here to see him.

21:50.413 --> 21:55.062
Haber: No need, this way.

23:00.756 --> 23:02.678
Albert: A glorious day!

23:02.679 --> 23:03.992
Assistant: It's raining,
Professor Einstein.

23:03.993 --> 23:05.146
Albert: Let it rain!

23:05.147 --> 23:08.322
Hilbert made a mistake!

23:09.858 --> 23:11.299
And so, when the next eclipse

23:11.300 --> 23:14.728
is upon us, these
calculations will explain,

23:14.729 --> 23:18.765
once and for all, relativity and

23:18.766 --> 23:23.128
the reason for mercury's
pesky orbit around the sun.

23:23.830 --> 23:29.282
There, it is complete.

23:31.458 --> 23:37.549
[Applause].

23:42.129 --> 23:48.606
♪

23:55.045 --> 23:57.159
Clara?

23:57.160 --> 23:59.786
Clara, what a nice surprise.

23:59.787 --> 24:01.837
But there's little use
in freezing to death

24:01.838 --> 24:03.280
before our time.

24:03.281 --> 24:04.273
Shall we?

24:04.274 --> 24:05.522
Clara: How are the boys?

24:05.523 --> 24:06.933
Do tell me some news of them.

24:06.934 --> 24:08.118
Albert: Clara, what is it?

24:08.119 --> 24:10.586
Surely you haven't come
for news of my boys.

24:10.587 --> 24:12.990
Clara: I'm worried about Fritz.

24:12.991 --> 24:15.682
He disappears all hours
of the day and night.

24:15.683 --> 24:17.861
And he's always wearing
that damn uniform,

24:17.862 --> 24:19.912
like a child playing dress up.

24:19.913 --> 24:21.418
Albert: I wouldn't be concerned.

24:21.419 --> 24:24.975
He's only helping Rathenau
produce gunpowder.

24:24.976 --> 24:28.889
Clara: He's working on
something else, Albert.

24:30.265 --> 24:33.211
Something terrible.

24:33.212 --> 24:38.471
I cannot live with a
man who engineers death.

24:41.064 --> 24:45.490
[Mouse squeaking].

24:56.479 --> 24:58.886
Albert: It's abominable.

25:01.638 --> 25:03.785
Haber: Have you ever seen
men twisting in agony

25:03.786 --> 25:05.195
on the battlefield, shot
through with bullets?

25:05.196 --> 25:09.232
Or witnessed the
horror in an infirmary

25:09.233 --> 25:10.771
as sepsis overtakes a body?

25:10.772 --> 25:12.854
That's abominable, Albert.

25:12.855 --> 25:15.546
This, this is humane.

25:15.547 --> 25:18.847
Albert: You'd burn a man's
insides, make him drown

25:18.848 --> 25:20.450
in his own phlegm?

25:20.451 --> 25:21.635
Haber: They're
slaughtering our boys.

25:21.636 --> 25:23.686
Albert: Because
we attacked them.

25:23.687 --> 25:25.417
Haber: Are you
taking their side?

25:25.418 --> 25:28.012
Albert: I'm taking
the side of humanity.

25:28.013 --> 25:29.166
Haber: Sitting on your hands.

25:29.167 --> 25:31.345
That's a convenient vantage
point from which to judge.

25:31.346 --> 25:32.819
Great men of history
aren't remembered

25:32.820 --> 25:34.262
for doing nothing, Albert.

25:34.263 --> 25:37.979
They are remembered for taking
action when no one else would.

25:37.980 --> 25:41.152
Albert: Ah, I see, so
you're doing this for glory.

25:41.153 --> 25:43.876
Haber: No, I'm doing
it to save lives.

25:43.877 --> 25:45.831
Albert: Fritz, you're
not making any sense.

25:45.832 --> 25:48.106
Haber: We will only
need to use it once.

25:48.107 --> 25:52.337
The french, the Russians, they
will see the power we wield and

25:52.338 --> 25:53.843
will have no choice
but to surrender before

25:53.844 --> 25:55.124
any more people die.

25:55.125 --> 25:57.047
Albert: My friend, listen to me.

25:57.048 --> 25:58.842
You don't have to go
through with this.

25:58.843 --> 26:00.444
It's not too late.

26:00.445 --> 26:01.983
We're scientists.

26:01.984 --> 26:04.483
Not purveyors of
death and destruction.

26:04.484 --> 26:08.104
Haber: During times of peace a
scientist belongs to the world.

26:08.105 --> 26:12.498
But during times of war,
he belongs to his country.

26:19.577 --> 26:24.865
Albert: Peace cannot be
kept by force, Fritz.

26:24.866 --> 26:29.547
It can only be achieved
by understanding.

26:34.864 --> 26:38.072
♪

26:39.928 --> 26:41.401
Do you know, max?

26:41.402 --> 26:44.834
What Fritz has been working on?

26:48.388 --> 26:50.085
Max?

26:50.086 --> 26:55.282
Planck: They say they will
give him a medal, a medal.

26:57.265 --> 26:58.802
Albert: Oh, Max.

26:58.803 --> 27:01.270
Planck: He was killed
at a battle in Verdun.

27:01.271 --> 27:05.505
They told me he faced his final
moments with great courage.

27:07.840 --> 27:10.567
Albert: I'm sure he did.

27:13.673 --> 27:16.685
Planck: You really think so?

27:16.686 --> 27:19.793
Because all I can picture is the
little boy who ran into my arms

27:19.794 --> 27:23.964
when the neighbor's
dog barked at him.

27:24.634 --> 27:28.638
That little boy,
lying in a cold field

27:28.639 --> 27:32.648
without his papa to hold him.

27:33.511 --> 27:39.122
God, I can only imagine how
scared he must have been.

27:40.369 --> 27:42.131
Albert: You should
be with your family.

27:42.132 --> 27:46.140
Come, come, I'll take you home.

27:47.259 --> 27:53.351
Planck: You were right to
defy Rathenau's call to arms.

27:53.829 --> 27:56.814
Albert: Right and wrong become
blurred in times like these.

27:56.842 --> 28:01.112
Planck: I signed their
damn war manifesto.

28:01.113 --> 28:05.583
And now it feels like I signed
my own son's death warrant.

28:08.821 --> 28:13.258
We can't just stand
by any longer, can we?

28:15.361 --> 28:20.465
♪

28:25.487 --> 28:28.056
Nicolai: Your good name will
draw the attention we need.

28:28.057 --> 28:31.225
Albert: I'm afraid the attention
may not be what you want.

28:31.226 --> 28:34.862
Many of my opponents think I'm
a traitor for opposing the war.

28:34.863 --> 28:36.731
Nicolai: To stand for your
principles when all others

28:36.732 --> 28:41.035
have forgotten theirs
isn't traitorous.

28:41.228 --> 28:44.096
It's patriotic.

28:53.555 --> 28:56.890
Soldier: The wind
is picking up, sir.

28:59.160 --> 29:02.596
Haber: Inform the
general we are ready.

29:10.138 --> 29:16.109
♪

29:23.885 --> 29:29.856
♪

29:36.965 --> 29:41.868
♪

29:46.641 --> 29:51.478
♪

29:57.352 --> 30:02.956
[Coughing].

30:08.129 --> 30:14.368
♪

30:22.143 --> 30:29.116
♪

30:36.357 --> 30:42.829
♪

30:47.995 --> 30:50.032
General: To a true hero!

30:50.033 --> 30:52.168
The English papers are
calling Captain Haber's gas

30:52.169 --> 30:53.769
the "death cloud."

30:53.770 --> 30:56.038
The enemy will surely
surrender soon thanks to

30:56.039 --> 30:59.709
our gracious host,
to Captain Haber!

30:59.710 --> 31:01.911
All: To Captain Haber!

31:03.714 --> 31:05.881
Haber: Yes, well, um, thank you.

31:05.883 --> 31:08.184
But even victory isn't worth
letting a fine lamb shank

31:08.185 --> 31:10.686
turn cold, so, please.

31:12.308 --> 31:15.243
Woman: I've heard rumors the
kaiser himself is to bestow

31:15.244 --> 31:17.545
a medal on your husband.

31:17.546 --> 31:19.981
You must be very
proud, Frau Haber.

31:29.227 --> 31:31.428
General: Whatever grand
invention will you contrive

31:31.429 --> 31:34.031
next, Captain Haber?

31:35.433 --> 31:39.069
Haber: At the moment, I'm still
trying to perfect this one.

31:39.070 --> 31:42.039
We need a more efficient
means to deploy the gas.

31:42.040 --> 31:45.208
General: I think it's
quite efficient already.

31:45.209 --> 31:47.010
[Gunshot].

31:53.751 --> 31:56.086
Haber: Clara!

31:56.621 --> 32:00.424
No, no, no.

32:12.476 --> 32:13.843
Paperboy: The war is over!

32:13.844 --> 32:15.893
Troops to return home.

32:15.894 --> 32:17.689
Armistice signed!

32:17.690 --> 32:19.455
The war is over!

32:20.093 --> 32:24.038
Elsa: Albert?

32:24.581 --> 32:26.951
The kaiser has fled.

32:26.952 --> 32:28.426
The war is finished.

32:28.427 --> 32:30.673
Einstein: Thank God, Elsa.

32:33.491 --> 32:36.859
Elsa: It says here
we're a democracy now.

32:37.625 --> 32:42.146
Einstein: Demokratia,
rule by the people.

32:43.202 --> 32:46.634
Let's hope the people have
their heads on straight.

32:46.984 --> 32:49.129
Elsa: Oh, my love.

32:49.130 --> 32:52.499
Don't fill your brilliant head
fill with gloomy thoughts.

32:53.714 --> 32:56.057
It's finally finished.

32:58.554 --> 33:00.413
Einstein: Yet I cannot
help but feel somehow

33:00.414 --> 33:02.400
it's only just begun.

33:02.401 --> 33:05.257
Paperboy: Troops to return home!

33:05.414 --> 33:07.207
Armistice signed!

33:07.208 --> 33:09.167
The war is over!

33:19.837 --> 33:22.051
Man: Please, spare some coin?

33:27.047 --> 33:29.034
Elsa: Albert, there's
a telegram for you.

33:29.035 --> 33:31.502
Einstein: Britain,
the United States, Russia,

33:31.503 --> 33:34.194
they all want reparations.

33:34.195 --> 33:38.168
France is threatening to occupy
the Ruhr if we don't pay.

33:38.169 --> 33:40.251
Forgiveness never comes cheap.

33:40.252 --> 33:43.364
Elsa: It's from
Arthur Eddington.

33:49.323 --> 33:50.604
What is it?

33:50.605 --> 33:52.976
Einstein: A silver
lining, it seems.

33:52.977 --> 33:55.604
"U-boats no longer threat, stop.

33:55.605 --> 33:59.354
Will sail to Africa, will
photograph eclipse, stop."

33:59.355 --> 34:00.860
Elsa: Albert, that's
wonderful news.

34:00.861 --> 34:04.998
Einstein: "Relativity
proof imminent, stop."

34:05.508 --> 34:07.943
I cannot wait to read that
in the scientific journals,

34:07.944 --> 34:11.216
hopefully with a
little more flair.

34:15.027 --> 34:16.179
What is it?

34:16.181 --> 34:18.455
Elsa: You can forget about
the journals, Albert.

34:18.456 --> 34:21.788
When you're proved right, your
name is going be printed in

34:21.789 --> 34:24.097
every newspaper around
the entire globe.

34:24.098 --> 34:25.186
You'll be famous.

34:25.187 --> 34:26.179
Einstein: Don't be silly.

34:26.181 --> 34:27.302
I'm a scientist.

34:27.303 --> 34:28.518
Elsa: They'll want interviews.

34:28.520 --> 34:30.601
They'll want to know
all about your life.

34:30.603 --> 34:33.583
Your family, me.

34:33.583 --> 34:35.505
Einstein: We'll tell them
you are my social secretary.

34:35.507 --> 34:37.462
Elsa: It took the neighbors
a couple of months.

34:37.463 --> 34:39.994
Imagine the journalists
clambering for a story,

34:39.995 --> 34:43.614
how long until they discover
that you are living in sin,

34:43.616 --> 34:46.306
with a divorcée,
who is your first cousin?

34:46.308 --> 34:47.717
Einstein: Who cares
what they think.

34:47.717 --> 34:49.996
Elsa: I care.

34:51.629 --> 34:53.743
Einstein: Elsa, I've asked
Mileva for a divorce

34:53.744 --> 34:55.505
in every way imaginable.

34:55.507 --> 34:58.006
Elsa: Then you
must ask her again.

34:58.007 --> 34:59.641
Make her an offer of some kind.

34:59.642 --> 35:01.627
Einstein: We don't have any
more Deutschmarks to give!

35:01.628 --> 35:02.621
Elsa: Fritz does.

35:02.622 --> 35:04.095
He would lend to you.

35:04.096 --> 35:06.106
Einstein: I cannot take blood
money from that warmonger.

35:06.107 --> 35:08.230
Elsa: Well you had better
think of something.

35:08.231 --> 35:11.211
Because it's one thing for me to
withstand the shaming stares

35:11.212 --> 35:12.685
of our neighbors.

35:12.686 --> 35:14.191
But you cannot
expect me to do that

35:14.192 --> 35:15.766
in front of the entire world.

35:18.872 --> 35:21.374
Einstein: I need the divorce.

35:21.949 --> 35:23.550
Mileva: Are you asking me?

35:23.551 --> 35:25.990
Or is it Elsa?

35:28.134 --> 35:30.858
Einstein: I'm sorry I could
not be what you needed, Mileva.

35:30.859 --> 35:33.421
Mileva: What about
Hans and Eduard?

35:33.422 --> 35:35.313
All they needed was
a reliable father.

35:35.314 --> 35:37.941
Einstein: You took
them away from me.

35:37.942 --> 35:40.605
I didn't.

35:41.851 --> 35:45.024
A British astronomer is heading
for Africa in a few months time

35:45.025 --> 35:48.645
to capture the solar eclipse.

35:48.646 --> 35:50.408
The first one in years.

35:50.409 --> 35:51.755
Mileva: You're sure
you're right this time?

35:51.756 --> 35:53.485
Your equations are co-variant?

35:53.486 --> 35:54.606
Einstein: Yes.

35:54.607 --> 35:56.210
They will define the
general relativity

35:56.211 --> 35:58.809
of all forms of motion.

35:59.544 --> 36:02.202
Mileva: It's an
extraordinary achievement.

36:02.203 --> 36:03.998
Einstein: And you were
there to help me at

36:03.999 --> 36:06.305
the beginning of it all.

36:06.306 --> 36:07.876
I will never forget that.

36:07.877 --> 36:11.561
Mileva: Ah, recognition from the
greatest scientist in the world.

36:11.562 --> 36:12.555
At last.

36:12.556 --> 36:14.285
My career is complete.

36:14.286 --> 36:18.104
Einstein: There's already
much discussion of a Nobel.

36:19.030 --> 36:21.658
You know, it comes with a
great deal of prize money.

36:21.659 --> 36:23.677
I want you to have it.

36:23.678 --> 36:24.766
All of it.

36:24.767 --> 36:27.458
Mileva: You want to
pay me for a divorce.

36:27.459 --> 36:29.446
Einstein: You deserve to
be taken care of, Dollie.

36:29.447 --> 36:30.695
Mileva: Do not call me that.

36:30.696 --> 36:32.618
Einstein: I'm offering you
more money than either of us

36:32.619 --> 36:33.836
has ever seen, Mileva.

36:33.837 --> 36:34.831
You need this.

36:34.832 --> 36:36.304
Don't be proud.

36:36.305 --> 36:37.266
Mileva: Get out.

36:37.267 --> 36:38.900
Einstein: If not for
you, do it for the boys.

36:38.901 --> 36:41.821
Mileva: I said get out!

36:52.235 --> 36:56.308
Einstein: What more
do you want from me?

37:12.523 --> 37:15.246
Hans: Why are you doing
this to yourself, mother?

37:15.247 --> 37:16.752
He obviously wants
nothing to do with us.

37:16.753 --> 37:20.410
He hasn't since he left
me sitting on that step.

37:21.337 --> 37:23.290
Just give him what he wants.

37:23.291 --> 37:25.791
He'll be out of our lives
and we can all move forward,

37:25.792 --> 37:28.134
once and for all.

37:50.662 --> 37:52.937
Elsa: Well?

37:52.938 --> 37:55.953
Einstein: She finally agreed.

37:57.681 --> 38:01.498
But it comes with
a terrible price.

38:09.187 --> 38:12.263
Magistrate: State the
reason for your divorce.

38:12.264 --> 38:14.828
Einstein: Adultery,
Herr Richter.

38:14.829 --> 38:16.718
Magistrate: And who
is the guilty party?

38:16.719 --> 38:18.898
Einstein: I am, Herr Richter.

38:18.899 --> 38:23.128
I have been living with Elsa
Einstein, divorced löwenthal,

38:23.129 --> 38:27.616
for approximately four years,
and have had continued

38:27.617 --> 38:30.761
intimate relations with her.

38:31.142 --> 38:32.359
Magistrate: Did you bring proof?

38:32.360 --> 38:35.212
Albert: She's the woman sitting
behind me, Herr Richter.

38:35.213 --> 38:38.228
Magistrate: Well please indicate
to the court, where she is.

38:45.533 --> 38:49.702
Is this true, madam?

38:50.180 --> 38:51.846
Elsa: Yes, Herr Richter.

38:51.847 --> 38:53.416
Magistrate: The provisions of
the divorce state that

38:53.417 --> 38:56.428
Mileva Maric, married
Einstein, will receive

38:56.429 --> 38:59.826
an annual stipend
of 9,000 Deutschmarks.

38:59.827 --> 39:03.063
Adding to this, Professor
Einstein promises her the full

39:03.064 --> 39:06.208
proceeds of a Nobel prize,
should he be awarded it.

39:09.635 --> 39:11.107
Very well.

39:11.108 --> 39:12.550
On to the children.

39:12.551 --> 39:16.171
Mileva Maric is to retain full
custody in Zürich, and the boys

39:16.172 --> 39:21.175
shall not be permitted to
visit their father in Berlin.

39:25.948 --> 39:28.003
Professor, do you object?

39:40.692 --> 39:43.771
Einstein: No, I do not object.

39:47.389 --> 39:50.149
Photographers: Dr and
Mrs Einstein, over here!

39:52.710 --> 39:54.792
Reporter: Dr Einstein,
Dr Einstein!

39:54.793 --> 39:56.748
What did you do when
you heard that Mr Eddington

39:56.749 --> 39:57.902
had proved your theory correct?

39:57.903 --> 40:00.017
Einstein: Well, I
went back to work.

40:00.018 --> 40:02.585
And I bought myself
a new violin.

40:04.248 --> 40:06.875
Reporter: Mr Eddington, what
did your pictures prove exactly?

40:06.876 --> 40:10.369
Eddington: That gravity bends
light passing next to the sun by

40:10.370 --> 40:14.411
approximately 1.7 arc seconds,
just as Einstein predicted.

40:15.626 --> 40:17.260
Reporter 2: Meaning what?

40:17.261 --> 40:19.600
Eddington: Meaning, gentlemen,
that the greatest of all

40:19.601 --> 40:24.055
scientific generalizations, the
laws of sir Isaac Newton,

40:24.056 --> 40:26.362
have just received their
first major modification

40:26.363 --> 40:28.189
in over two centuries.

40:28.190 --> 40:31.330
We are all witness to one of the
most resplendent achievements

40:31.331 --> 40:34.635
of human thought
in our lifetime.

40:35.145 --> 40:37.648
Write that down.

40:38.094 --> 40:39.471
Lenard: Relativity is a hoax.

40:39.472 --> 40:43.353
Arrhenius: Doctor Lenard, it was
just proven by Arthur Eddington.

40:44.151 --> 40:46.586
Lenard: What happens at the next
eclipse, when the results vary?

40:46.587 --> 40:48.220
You will look like fools.

40:48.221 --> 40:51.298
Our discoveries changed
science because they were

40:51.299 --> 40:52.804
grounded in facts.

40:52.805 --> 40:55.912
They weren't philosophical
conjectures cloaked in

40:55.913 --> 40:58.448
equations designed to deceive.

40:59.375 --> 41:01.906
As the Nobel selection
committee, it is your duty

41:01.907 --> 41:04.025
to know the difference.

41:06.106 --> 41:09.726
Einstein: They're
giving it to Max Planck.

41:09.727 --> 41:11.169
Elsa: Well, you always
said it was a shame how the

41:11.170 --> 41:13.861
Nobel committee overlooked
him all these years.

41:13.862 --> 41:15.784
Einstein: They're
giving it to Fritz, too.

41:15.785 --> 41:18.320
In chemistry.

41:18.574 --> 41:21.910
For his nitrogen trick.

41:23.253 --> 41:26.717
Elsa: Quite a year for
the Prussian Academy.

41:27.355 --> 41:31.361
Well, I'm sure a lovely
celebration will be in order.

41:31.362 --> 41:33.507
Einstein: I'm not going
if Fritz is to be honored.

41:33.508 --> 41:36.552
Elsa: Albert, if you insist
on condemning a man for his

41:36.553 --> 41:39.793
mistakes you must be willing to
applaud him for his triumphs.

41:40.399 --> 41:41.777
Fritz didn't start the war.

41:41.778 --> 41:43.828
Einstein: He's responsible
for thousands of deaths.

41:43.829 --> 41:47.097
Elsa: He also saved half
of Europe from starvation.

41:47.098 --> 41:48.603
Doesn't that mean something?

41:48.604 --> 41:50.303
Einstein: I cannot
congratulate a killer and

41:50.304 --> 41:51.648
call myself a pacifist.

41:51.649 --> 41:54.854
Elsa: But if you insist that
the worst disputes between two

41:54.855 --> 41:57.995
warring nations can be
resolved, then can't two

41:57.996 --> 42:00.723
old friends make peace?

42:07.130 --> 42:08.828
Planck: Albert!

42:08.829 --> 42:10.910
Einstein: What can
I say, old friend?

42:10.911 --> 42:13.346
It's about time
they honored you.

42:13.347 --> 42:16.587
How many years has it been since
you discovered light quanta?

42:17.066 --> 42:19.597
Planck: About 3,000.

42:19.598 --> 42:22.961
Einstein: Truly,
Max, congratulations.

42:22.962 --> 42:24.467
Planck: It should
have been yours.

42:24.468 --> 42:26.807
Einstein: Nonsense.

42:26.808 --> 42:29.023
You deserve it more than
any man in this room.

42:30.078 --> 42:32.064
Man: Excuse me, Dr Planck?

42:32.065 --> 42:35.625
Planck: We'll talk.

42:40.494 --> 42:46.490
♪

42:53.090 --> 42:54.435
Haber: Albert.

42:54.436 --> 42:59.050
Einstein: A Nobel in
chemistry, that is something.

42:59.051 --> 43:01.454
Haber: I'm not a genius
like you, Albert.

43:01.455 --> 43:04.275
All I did was see a problem
and find a way to fix it.

43:04.276 --> 43:05.941
That's what I try
to do, I suppose.

43:05.942 --> 43:07.030
Fix things.

43:07.031 --> 43:08.377
Einstein: Yes, of course.

43:08.378 --> 43:09.883
Or destroy them.

43:09.884 --> 43:11.454
Haber: That is entirely unfair.

43:11.455 --> 43:14.082
Einstein: Did you not invent a
new way to destroy human life?

43:14.083 --> 43:17.415
Haber: Yes, but that was
not my only innovation.

43:17.416 --> 43:20.556
I'm being honored tonight
for the good I've done.

43:20.557 --> 43:21.999
Einstein: Life
cannot be balanced

43:22.000 --> 43:24.979
like an equation, Fritz.

43:24.980 --> 43:28.156
Good deeds do not
erase the evil ones.

43:29.659 --> 43:33.380
Haber: I certainly pray to God
you're wrong for once, Albert.

43:35.781 --> 43:38.028
Einstein: Perhaps I
have been too harsh.

43:40.204 --> 43:42.483
Haber: Perhaps you haven't.

43:44.242 --> 43:45.459
Einstein: I never
told you, Fritz,

43:45.460 --> 43:49.274
how sorry I was, about Clara.

43:49.275 --> 43:50.459
Haber: We couldn't
manage to hold on to the

43:50.460 --> 43:53.251
more brilliant ones, could we?

43:53.889 --> 43:57.931
Photographer: Gentlemen, smile!

43:58.890 --> 44:00.363
Lenard: He didn't even
win the Nobel and yet

44:00.364 --> 44:02.414
still he graces our front pages.

44:02.415 --> 44:03.760
And not only in Berlin.

44:03.761 --> 44:07.931
Frankfurt, Paris, London,
New York, Tokyo, I could go on.

44:09.562 --> 44:12.125
Weyland: All about
"general relativity," yes.

44:12.126 --> 44:13.952
Lenard: Relativity,
politics, his hair,

44:13.953 --> 44:15.875
what he ate for breakfast.

44:15.876 --> 44:17.125
It's despicable.

44:17.126 --> 44:19.177
Weyland: It's to be expected.

44:19.178 --> 44:20.458
He's a Jew.

44:20.459 --> 44:22.734
A publicity-seeking
Jew who uses his influence

44:22.735 --> 44:24.977
for his own profit.

44:24.978 --> 44:28.696
Lenard: Well now, Herr Weyland,
I didn't quite say all that.

44:28.697 --> 44:32.157
Weyland: You are standing in the
German national people's party

44:32.158 --> 44:35.426
headquarters, Dr
Lenard, we aren't afraid

44:35.427 --> 44:37.381
to speak the truth here.

44:37.382 --> 44:40.073
In fact, I imagine my
candor is the very reason

44:40.074 --> 44:41.263
you've come to see me.

44:43.023 --> 44:46.840
Now, please, what
can I do for you?

44:47.990 --> 44:50.714
Lenard: I have a proposition
to make, but one with which

44:50.715 --> 44:53.823
I cannot afford to be
publicly associated.

44:53.824 --> 44:56.899
Weyland: You can be
assured of my discretion.

44:56.900 --> 45:00.426
Lenard: I read your paper
denouncing relativity.

45:00.427 --> 45:03.250
I think you deserve
a wider audience.

45:04.400 --> 45:07.957
Weyland: Albert Einstein has
engaged in a profit-grubbing

45:07.958 --> 45:10.585
promotion of his theory,
as our country suffers

45:10.586 --> 45:13.278
deprivation and indignity.

45:13.279 --> 45:15.457
And for what?

45:15.458 --> 45:19.719
For a lie, for a hoax.

45:19.720 --> 45:23.249
For a deception
unlike any other.

45:23.951 --> 45:27.187
Over the next two days, you
will hear from Germany's most

45:27.188 --> 45:30.200
preeminent scholars, who
will show you exactly how

45:30.201 --> 45:33.630
we've all been hoodwinked
by one enormous bluff.

45:33.631 --> 45:35.845
Einstein: Hear, hear!

45:38.149 --> 45:39.143
Oh, apologies.

45:39.144 --> 45:40.488
Continue, doctor Weyland.

45:40.489 --> 45:43.245
We all eagerly await
your scholarly proof.

45:43.246 --> 45:45.748
I'm sure it will be
very interesting.

45:46.483 --> 45:47.571
Elsa: What in God's
name were you thinking?!

45:47.572 --> 45:49.077
Einstein: It was a public
lecture and I was curious,

45:49.078 --> 45:50.456
so I went.

45:50.457 --> 45:52.700
I admit I didn't expect much,
but I also didn't expect it

45:52.701 --> 45:56.581
to be a packed house of
anti-Semitic imbeciles.

45:58.021 --> 45:59.302
Elsa: What are you doing?

45:59.303 --> 46:00.680
Einstein: Writing to the
Berliner Tageblatt to give

46:00.681 --> 46:02.378
my honest critique.

46:02.379 --> 46:03.692
Elsa: Albert, stop.

46:03.693 --> 46:05.712
You are sticking your
hand into a hornet's nest.

46:05.713 --> 46:07.892
These men are vindictive
and dangerous.

46:07.893 --> 46:09.878
Einstein: This world is
dangerous, Elsa, not because

46:09.879 --> 46:11.866
of those who do evil,
but because of those who

46:11.867 --> 46:14.590
look on and do nothing.

46:14.591 --> 46:16.352
I cannot do nothing.

46:16.353 --> 46:19.493
Lenard: "I admire Lenard as a
master of experimental physics.

46:19.494 --> 46:21.833
But he has not yet produced
anything outstanding

46:21.834 --> 46:23.564
in theoretical physics."

46:23.565 --> 46:25.967
Katharina: He wrote that?

46:25.968 --> 46:28.372
Lenard: On the front
of the damn newspaper!

46:28.373 --> 46:31.705
Jewish publishers, of course.

46:31.706 --> 46:34.878
"Lenard's objections to the
general theory of relativity

46:34.879 --> 46:37.602
are of such superficiality
that, up until now,

46:37.603 --> 46:40.423
I did not think it
necessary to answer them.

46:40.424 --> 46:43.214
I intend to make up for this."

46:46.289 --> 46:49.204
It's an affront!

46:49.205 --> 46:50.175
I will not stand for it!

46:50.176 --> 46:52.153
Katharina: Why would he assume
that you had anything to do

46:52.154 --> 46:53.628
with that lecture series?

46:53.629 --> 46:56.223
You did not even attend!

46:56.224 --> 46:59.716
Lenard: That huckster Weyland
listed me as a coming

46:59.717 --> 47:01.224
lecturer in the program.

47:01.225 --> 47:05.426
No doubt trying to add
my prestige to his cause.

47:07.699 --> 47:09.268
But it doesn't matter,

47:09.269 --> 47:13.471
Einstein obviously desires
a public battle,

47:15.134 --> 47:17.701
perhaps it's time I
enlisted some public allies.

